description:
This will be our first event. The day after this event is the start of the Google I/O 2013 Conference. The primary presentation at this event will be focused on the Google Web Toolkit (GWT).

#GDG Space Coast will be presenting on the 15th and 16th at the Google I/O Extended event in Orlando (UCF). That content will be presented/discussed at this meeting. This will include #gwt , #chromeos , and #chromebook . The GWT presentation will cover, 'what is Google Web Toolkit?', 'what's new in GWT', and 'how can i get started with GWT'?'.

There is no charge for the event and it is open to everyone who signs up here in advance.
title: GDG Space Coast Kickoff Meeting - Google Web Toolkit (GWT)

description:
Bring your laptops! This is the first in a series of events focused around the #GCDC 2013! Find out more about Google Cloud Developer Challenge 2013 and the $20,000 grand prize here: http://www.google.com/events/gcdc2013/

We will be starting out with 2 Code Camps focused on building web applications on Google App Engine. Then we will be holding 1-2 Code Camps focused on building a web front end with AngularJS. These events will be held on Saturday afternoons from 9/28 until the first round submission date on 11/21.

The focus of the code camp is learning and not competition. There will be people there to help and answer questions as you walk through the steps to build a web application including things like NoSQL and SQL datastores, Entities, Memcache, XMPP, Mail, Task Queues, Relationships, and the Channel API.

By the end of the 2nd App Engine Code Camp you should expect to have built your own fully functional web app using numerous powerful cloud features, deployed it to the cloud, and learned how to manage and track it.

After the Code Camp series is completed, starting approximately 10/26, the focus will turn to Hackathon meetups at the same times. We will be using the knowledge gained in the Code Camps to build a applications to enter into the #GCDC ! Start recruiting your team of 3 now (and don't forget to think about graphic artists and designers).

The App Engine Code Camps will be run based on #Java but you are welcome to attend and attempt to hack away using PHP, Go, or Python. You should be an advanced user of those languages if you decide to go that route though, as there will be less assistance available.
title: GDG Space Coast - GCDC Kickoff: App Engine Code Camp #1

description:
Bring your laptops! This is the second in a series of events focused around the #GCDC 2013! Find out more about Google Cloud Developer Challenge 2013 and the $20,000 grand prize here: http://www.google.com/events/gcdc2013/

The focus of the code camp is learning and not competition. There will be people there to help and answer questions as you walk through the steps to build a web application including things like Web Services, High Replication, Custom Domain, Queues and Backends, Warmup Requests, and Pagination.

Assuming you attended or completed Code Camp #1, by the end of the this Code Camp you should expect to have built your own fully functional web app using numerous powerful cloud features, deployed it to the cloud, and learned how to manage and track it.

If you want more information about App Engine, here are the slides that we shared at our last GDG event: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1sBn6_IcLbZBwEJf94dyu_7fddRptQj1pbho_iIQTuvo/edit?usp=sharing

The App Engine Code Camps will be run based on #Java but you are welcome to attend and attempt to hack away using PHP, Go, or Python. You should be an advanced user of those languages if you decide to go that route though, as there will be less assistance available.

If you plan to work along with us in Java, you should have basic knowledge and understanding of the following concepts: GAE concepts from Code Lab #1, Java syntax, object oriented concepts (objects, classes, interfaces, inheritance, modularity, etc), web servers, ORM concepts (Entities, JDO, JPA, etc), basic concepts of NoSQL and SQL databases, consumption of APIs, caching, Java Servlets, HTTP requests, JavaScript syntax, XML-Java Conversion, web services (REST and SOAP), and XML. Each of the 5 tutorials will build upon the previous tutorials.

Unfortunately, this event will not be streamed online and you must be in attendance at TrepHub to learn with us.

The code lab site that we'll be using is found here: http://googcloudlabs.appspot.com

Here are some slides to help with workarounds and tips for the code lab: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/12kxKC53k0E1o85X7iSAu3G-QXpqXauh3XAg_FJdOzG8/edit?usp=sharing﻿ Please feel free to leave comments if you have anything to add and we will integrate them into the document.
title: GDG Space Coast - GCDC: App Engine Code Camp #2

description:
Bring your laptops! This is the fourth in a series of events focused around the #GCDC 2013! Find out more about Google Cloud Developer Challenge 2013 and the $20,000 grand prizes here: http://www.google.com/events/gcdc2013/

This is the first front-end focused event for #GCDC. The primary topic is AngularJS. The focus of the code camp is learning and not competition. There will be people there to help and answer questions.

The agenda is still a work in progress, but here is the proposed agenda:
Introductory Video/Presentation
Setup and Configuration (fork from Github, verify HTTP Server, verify AngularJS configurations).
Presentation and selection of possible code lab tasks
Investigation and implementation of code labs
Review and merge of completed tasks into final application (hosted on GAE)

Unfortunately, this event will not be streamed online and you must be in attendance at TrepHub to learn with us.

TrepHub is located in the building across from city hall. We'll meet in the Co-Working Area. The entrance is on the street (Route 192).
title: GDG Space Coast: AngularJS Code Camp
